sitions. I'm filtering out the commented notes and focusing on the substantive Layer A and Layer B content. バッチ処理で構成される取引の場合、自動テストフレームワークを使って各バッチを連続実行することで、取引単体テストを実施できる。\n\n次に、メッセージング処理の場合を見ると、通常はリクエストと取引のスコープが同じなので、1リクエスト=1取引であれば取引単体テストは不要だが、複数のメッセージで取引が成立する場合は異なる。\n\nその場合、バッチ処理と同じアプローチで、各リクエストを連続実行することで取引単体テストを実施できる。また、ドキュメント参照として関連するユニットテストガイドへのリンクを確認している。 The base URL is empty, so I won't include any official documentation URLs. Now I'm moving on to compose the content sections, starting with the first one about online transaction unit testing in screen processing environments.\n\nI'm listing out the specific request-level test items that can't be verified through other means—checking that browser inputs reach the server correctly, validating screen transitions through anchor tags, and ensuring JavaScript executes properly. I'm also including reference diagrams for the screen transition flow and the scope of transaction unit testing.\n\nFor the next section, I'm considering how batch processes factor into transaction unit testing. When transactions consist of sequential batch operations, the unit tests need to verify those combinations work together. Using an automated testing framework allows running each batch in sequence to complete the transaction unit test.\n\nThen for messaging scenarios, the request and transaction scope typically align. If it's one request per transaction, no unit testing is needed. But when multiple messages form a single transaction, I can apply the same approach as batch processing—running sequential tests for each request to validate the complete transaction.\n\nThere's an important distinction though: when multiple messages are involved, like an initial inquiry message followed by a processing request, that's when this sequential testing approach becomes necessary. For multiple messages that form a single transaction—like when a preliminary inquiry message comes first, followed by the actual request—I can handle this similarly to batch processing by running sequential tests for each request. Now I'm thinking about the document structure and what the overall title should be, since all three sections use the same heading level without a parent title above them. The filename suggests this is a unit test outline document, and since all the content focuses on 取引単体テスト (transaction unit testing), I'll use that as the main title. There's no h1 heading with the standard RST underline, so I'll work with the first available heading structure in the document.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":18171,"cache_read_input_tokens":18643,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":18171,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9efdcdad-6e52-4099-9c58-2096c3245c4b","uuid":"f78d24fc-f3df-49f9-98b9-6c31204bb903"}
